ARGUMENT.

He on whom in his natal hour Apollo smiles, wetting his lips in Castalian dew, is found in our age either drawing incautious youth into Venus' snares by corrupting verse, or bestowing his leisured hours upon μ celebration of mad wars, turning Aonia to a pool of blood. Religion lies neglected‚ or, if it finds a poet, 'tis one whose note grates on scrannel pipe of straw. Both rocks of offence does Ramsay shun, for he sounds strains worthy of the Muse, worthy also of the Power Divine. The peaks of Parnassus here rise conjoined with the rock of Mount Zi0n; Jordan mingles its waves with Castaly.
